Author: @Roudmanlogan
Comment:
Just a fun fact:

In the "Mind the Gap" mission from "Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 3," the atmosphere is dark and tense as the heroes maneuver through abandoned warehouses and narrow London Underground tunnels. This scene encapsulates the chilling words of Makarov: "It doesnâ€™t take the most powerful nation on Earth to create the next global conflict, just the will of a single man."

In the trailer the camera zooms in on a soldier emerging from the wreckage of a train pursuit 0:55. Dim light filters through shattered headlights and flickering lamps, casting an eerie ambiance. Amidst the darkness of war, this light symbolizes a glimmer of hope, underscoring humanity's resilience.

The soldier, barely recognizable, embodies the anonymity and potent influence of individual will. In the chaos of conflict, anyone possesses the potential to reshape events. Nearby, the train wreckage, once a symbol of unstoppable force, now lies in ruin and disarray, demonstrating how even formidable powers can be halted by one person's unwavering resolve.

Makarov himself, a central figure in the franchise, embodies this notionâ€”a single individual whose decisions can alter the course of global events. His presence in the narrative underscores the profound impact of individual actions amidst the complexities of war.

The combination of Makarovâ€™s chilling quote and the vivid scene invites reflection on the power of individual determination to shape the world, for better or worse.

Author: @gortimustidditus
Comment:
I see why people are so upset about this campaign, lmao. It's so disjointed and not much makes sense? And the maps/missions seem so rushed like multiplayer maps thrown in with a boring mission pasted on top.

The cinematics and acting very good though!. 

I laughed when Price got stuck in the "super extra lethal chemical gas and then passed out. It seemed like it was a big deal and then he just woke up on another helicopter and ready to go? 

Let's just say the rest of the campaign after he passes out from the gas is a fever dream and never happened because holy shit the writing and missions are so lackluster! They're lucky they had such good cinematics and the VA's had such good charisma. It's the only thing that saves this game.

Rewriting new MW3

Makarov causes a 9/11 in London destroying the clock tower causing the NATO Allience to call out Russia and prepare for war. KOMMI coups Russia and starts an incursion into Eastern Europe.

These are where the missions take place

Mission 1- The Beginning (London)
Mission 2- Makarov (Russia)
Mission 3 - Berlin
Mission 4 - Warsaw
Mission 5- Kaliningrad 
Mission 6- Lithuania
Mission 7- Heneleski
Mission 8- Istanbul
Mission 9- Tibilisi
Mission 10- Caucasian Mountians
Mission 11- Turkmenistan
Mission 12- Northern Iran
Mission 13- Kabul
Mission 14- The Caspian Sea
Mission 15- Final Mission. Task force 141 joins the force in Moscow. In a panic macorov orders an atomic missile onto New York City. Macarov also suicide bombs Moscow. Soap is killed in the explosion and Price is injured. We are also introduced to the Yuri character who is fighting in the Russian Resistance. Then DLC will happen about finishing the job, retaking Russia, and stoping Nolan, Macarovs successor.

Comment:
The reason This version of "No Russian" was made, was a poor attempt to push an "Anti-Gun Rethoric", as the Glock used was _supposed_ to be a Quote/Unquote "Ghost Gun made from Ceramic Parts that is invisible to metal detectors", which is why it was _White..._ Which makes _zero_ sense as a "Ghost Gun" is simply a gun with 3D Printed parts, and thus, won't show up in a National Gun Registry because it lacks a serial number.

And the Casings are made of _BRASS_ for the same reason as the barrel, which show up on Metal Detectors as well.

Activision basically thinks people are completely lacking in brains and will follow a rethoric that is utter Pigwash.

I really hate open combat missions they are basically the bad missions of the Battlefield campaigns that was present in Battlefield 1 & 5. 1 they where alright but 5 they where so boring I never finished the game. Same feeling here. I prefer some choice like you had in COD Black ops 2 & Infinite warfare where you can chose what mission to play next & have some control over how to approach the mission but not making me run around a silly map & clear objectives & hunt collectables. The 1st open combat one is fine but the 2nd just ends up being kinda boring as you are on your own & feel like a one man army instead of being in a small fire team where you are kinda leading the battle which would be a far more interesting version of this concept. Halo basically does this & it does it the best unlike MW3 which kinda makes levels feel odd. Like where did ghost go after the jump? he was with you right? I haven't finished it yet but I don't feel confident in the rest of the game. So glad Game pass let me play it without wasting money on it.
Edit: I think your point about Solo vs Co-op explains why I prefer the style in Halo because you never really play a Halo game alone you usually have someone on mic or on your sofa playing it together & trying to work together or against each other allowing the open nature to allow fun tactics. I also think the Tom Clancy games like Rainbow Six the older ones do similar missions well by allowing you to command fireteams which is similar to what you do in Black ops 2's special operations missions where you basically command squads to take multiple points or defend multiple points. Its basically too lonely to work.

1. Firing Cycle
	â€¢	When the trigger is pulled, the striker-fired mechanism releases the firing pin, which strikes the primer of the chambered round.
	â€¢	This ignites the gunpowder inside the cartridge, creating high-pressure gas that propels the bullet down the barrel.

2. Recoil and Ejection
	â€¢	The force of the shot pushes the slide rearward while the barrel unlocks and tilts slightly downward.
	â€¢	As the slide moves back, the spent casing is extracted and ejected from the chamber.
	â€¢	The recoil spring then forces the slide forward, chambering a new round from the magazine.

3. Reset and Ready to Fire
	â€¢	The striker is partially cocked as the slide returns to its forward position.
